@csantanapr was the intention to show the input arguments to the action?
the way it's written now - thanks @cfjedimaster for pointing this out - it suggests that's the response from the action which is of course wrong.

should we show both? input + output explicitly (two different sections)?

Stranger still
```javascript
function main(params) {
	return new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {
		var result;

		try {
			result = params.cannot.be.found;
		} catch(e) {
			console.log("I caught e: " + e);
			reject(e);
                        return;
		}

		resolve(result);
	});
}
```

This expanded version still produces the `{ "error": {} }` result but the logs clearly show that `e` is the exception you would expect to get. I think we can go back to blaming something going wrong with the Node runtime's handling of this situation.

@markusthoemmes 

Is it planned to externalize the entitlement in the other way? 
We have been working on integrate openwhisk with [Keystone](https://docs.openstack.org/developer/keystone/)  using this feature.

there is another related issue: when the `entity` is empty, this will "run" twice on a failure (first rejects, tries the second):
```
entity(as[Option[JsObject]]) {
    body => process(body)
} ~ entity(as[FormData]) {
     form => process(Some(form.fields.toMap.toJson.asJsObject))
}
```
